Bring a large #pot{} of water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Trim @scallions{2}. Thinly slice greens; cut whites into 1⁄2-inch batons. Gently
crush @peanuts{1/2%ounce} in their bag.

Once water is boiling, add @lo mein noodles{4.5%ounce} to pot. Cook, stirring
occasionally, until al dente, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Drain and set aside.

Pat @pork chops{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}; thinly slice crosswise into
strips. Season all over with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add pork
in an even layer; cook, stirring occasionally, until browned and cooked through,
~{3-5%minutes}.

Turn off heat. Transfer pork to a #plate{}; wipe out pan.

Heat another drizzle of @cooking oil{} in pan used for pork over medium-high heat.
Add scallion whites, @coleslaw mix{4%ounce}, @garlic powder{1%teaspoon},
@salt{}, and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until veggies begin to
soften, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Return pork to pan with veggies.

Add @sweet soy glaze{4%tablespoon}, @sweet Thai chili sauce{1%ounce}, 1/3 cup
water, and as much @Sriracha{1%teaspoon} as you like; stir to combine.

Add drained noodles and half the peanuts to pan; remove from heat. Stir in
@butter{1%tbsp}. Taste and season with salt and pepper if desired.

Divide lo mein between shallow #bowls{}. Sprinkle with scallion greens and
remaining peanuts. Serve.

> Pork is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.